data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages — you'd just see "expected true, got false."

Here's an improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // CollectionAssert for collection-level checks
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // Assert.IsTrue is fine for predicate checks, but add a message
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of IsTrue for null checks
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | Shows actual vs expected |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent & message |
| `users.Single(...)` | `users.SingleOrDefault(...)` | Avoids exception masking the assertion |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `Contains(collection, item)` — membership check
- `AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
- `AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same items, same order
- `AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` — no duplicates

If you're open to a third-party library, **FluentAssertions** makes this even more expressive:

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
